<section xml:id="sec-opamp-ideal" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>The Ideal OpAmp</title>
    <p>
        The schematic symbol for an ideal op-amp is provided in <xref ref="fig-opamp-ideal-schematic"/>, where <m>V_-</m> and <m>V_+</m> are called the <term>inverting input</term> and <term>non-inverting input</term> respectively. The amplifier output is given as <m>V_\text{out}</m>. Op-amps require an external voltage source for operation, just as transistors require <m>V_{CC}</m> and <m>V_{EE}</m> as supply voltages. These two supply voltages are marked as <m>V_{s+}</m> and <m>V_{s-}</m>, though these connections are sometimes left out in circuit diagrams. 
        <figure xml:id="fig-opamp-ideal-schematic">
            <caption>Schematic symbol for an ideal op-amp. The inverting and non-inverting inputs are specified as <m>V_-</m> and <m>V_+</m>. The two voltages <m>V_{s+}</m> and <m>V_{s-}</m> are supplied by an external power source.</caption>
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    <xi:include parse="text" href="./figures/fig-opamp-ideal-schematic.ptx" />
                </latex-image>  
            </image>
        </figure>
    </p>
